## 7. Performance Trade-offs

### 7.1 Memory vs Coverage

**vLLM**:
- **Memory**: Moderate (dual-mode captures both FULL and PIECEWISE)
- **Coverage**: Excellent (handles prefill and decode)
- **Flexibility**: High (automatic mode downgrade)

**SGLang**:
- **Memory**: Higher (two-tier system + per-shape compilation)
- **Coverage**: Excellent (standard + piecewise covers all cases)
- **Flexibility**: Very high (torch.compile + graphs)

**TensorRT-LLM**:
- **Memory**: Lower (decode-only)
- **Coverage**: Limited (decode batches only)
- **Flexibility**: Low (fixed decode-only strategy)

### 7.2 Warmup Time

| System | Warmup Overhead | Reason |
|--------|----------------|---------|
| **vLLM** | Low-Medium | Configurable warmups (default 0-2) |
| **SGLang** | Medium-High | Two-tier capture + torch.compile |
| **TensorRT-LLM** | Low | Automatic on first execution |

### 7.3 Runtime Performance

**CPU Overhead Reduction**:
- **vLLM**: ~10-30% improvement with FULL mode
- **SGLang**: ~15-40% improvement (more with piecewise)
- **TensorRT-LLM**: ~20-50% improvement (TensorRT optimization + graphs)

**Latency Improvement**:
- **vLLM**: Better for decode-heavy workloads
- **SGLang**: Better for mixed prefill/decode workloads
- **TensorRT-LLM**: Best for pure decode workloads

### 7.4 Flexibility vs Performance

**vLLM**:
- ✅ Automatic mode selection
- ✅ Attention backend compatibility
- ✅ LoRA specialization
- ⚠️ Requires warmup configuration

**SGLang**:
- ✅ Handles variable prefill lengths
- ✅ torch.compile integration
- ✅ Hidden state capture modes
- ⚠️ Higher memory overhead
- ⚠️ Complex configuration

**TensorRT-LLM**:
- ✅ Automatic capture
- ✅ Minimal configuration
- ✅ TensorRT optimization
- ❌ Decode-only limitation
- ❌ No prefill graph support

